## 6. Word Count, Tone & Format

### Recommended Word Count
**2,800–3,500 words** for the full article.

Rationale: Competitor pages are extremely thin (Green St. Realty: ~200 words; Keystone Management: ~300 words; StreetEasy pages: listing-only, no editorial content). This is not a space where depth is the norm — which means a well-structured 2,800–3,500 word guide with tables, definitions, and checklists will dramatically outperform every current organic result on comprehensiveness. Claude's response alone contained ~600 words of structured content; the full article should expand every framework Claude introduced to 3–5x that depth with local market data and practical tools.

Do not exceed 3,500 words. Padding degrades AI citability. Every section must earn its place.

### Tone of Voice
**Practical, direct, and expert-neutral** — the tone of a knowledgeable friend who has rented dozens of apartments, not a real estate agent trying to close a deal or a landlord trying to fill a unit.

Specific tone guidelines:
- Write in second person ("you," "your") throughout
- Use short sentences for definitions and rules (AI engines cite concise declarative statements)
- Avoid superlatives ("best," "most amazing," "perfect") — use specific, qualified claims instead
- Do not use promotional language when describing platforms or brightplace — describe capabilities, not marketing
- Assume the reader is intelligent but time-poor: lead every section with the answer, then provide supporting context

### Required Content Formats

| Format | Where to Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Comparison tables (4 minimum)** | Market tier costs, platform comparison, layout types, amenity checklist | Claude's response was structured as tables; AI engines pattern-match to tabular data for citations |
| **Step-by-step numbered lists** | Application readiness section, "how to search by location" section | Supports AI "how to" citation format and Google featured snippet eligibility |
| **Definition callout blocks** | First use of each defined term (net effective rent, 3x rule, split floor plan, etc.) | Bold term + colon + one-sentence definition is the most citable formatting unit in this space |
| **Checklist (bullet format)** | Amenity checklist, application documents checklist, bedroom inspection checklist | Renters want to act — checklists support both engagement and AI "what to look for" citations |
| **FAQ block with Q&A schema** | Final section | FAQPage schema is the fastest path to Google SERP features; also directly feeds AI engine FAQ citations |
| **Inline data anchors** | Every pricing claim | Specific numbers (e.g., "$1,400–$1,700/month") are cited by AI engines; vague ranges are not |

